Ensemble Learning: The Use of the Random Forest Algorithm to Perform Human Activity Recognition From Wearable Accelerometer Data.¶

We will implement a series of random forests and train the models to discern one of six potential human activities being performed, based solely on the accelerometer data of our dataset. Each training iteration of the random forest will have slightly different hyperparameter tunings, and we will then determine the best model from the resulting accuracy metrics.

The random forest algorithm is robust against overfitting. Although they leverage the ability of decision trees to fit training data very well, the use of a random subset of training features produces a set of decision trees that will be distinctly random from one another. This will ensure that the trees are not highly correlated, and the use of "bagging" (bootstrap aggregation) as part of the random forest algorithm ensures that the high variance of the standard decision tree algo is also mitigated.

The Human Activity Recognition database was built from the recordings of 30 study participants performing activities of daily living (ADL) while carrying a waist-mounted smartphone with embedded inertial sensors. The objective is to classify activities into one of the six activities performed:

  • WALKING
  • WALKING UPSTAIRS
  • WALKING DOWNSTAIRS
  • SITTING
  • STANDING
  • LAYING

Summary¶

With 561 feature vectors, each comprised of sensor signals (accelerometer and gyroscope), we have been able to use the data to discern the difference between 6 classes of human activity. We began with a dimensionality reduction in order to visualize the 561-dimensional data space, reduced down to 3 principal components containing the majority of the original variance, plotted onto a 3-dimensional set of axes. The datapoints were found to clearly express 2 major clusters of data, with each cluster containing the 3 subgroups within those clusters of data.

A series of random forest classifiers were fitted and analyzed for their respective predictive power. The criteria of Gini and Entropy were tried, as well as the maximum depth of the trees, and the minimum impurity decrease to split nodes. A random forest of 59 sub-trees was selected as the best performing model of the set. A max depth of 20 and a minimum impurity decrease of 0.0 were found the be ideal.

There was a discernable difficulty in classifying the difference between walking downstairs, walking upstairs, and general walking. The observed activities of walking downstairs and especially walking upstairs were being misclassified as walking, and walking downstairs was also misclassified as walking upstairs. Even so, the rest of the human activities were relatively easily classified with a high measure of recall and precision. The classification report shows relatively good performance, with an average recall of 0.94, and an average f1-score of 0.94. The worst f1-score corresponds to class 4 (walking downstairs), with a score of 0.90.

Description of the Experiment¶

The experiments have been carried out with a group of 30 volunteers within an age bracket of 19-48 years. Each person performed six activities (WALKING, WALKING UPSTAIRS, WALKING DOWNSTAIRS, SITTING, STANDING, LAYING) wearing a smartphone (Samsung Galaxy S II) on the waist. Using its embedded accelerometer and gyroscope, we captured 3-axial linear acceleration and 3-axial angular velocity at a constant rate of 50Hz. The experiments have been video-recorded to label the data manually. The obtained dataset has been randomly partitioned into two sets, where 70% of the volunteers was selected for generating the training data and 30% the test data.

The sensor signals (accelerometer and gyroscope) were pre-processed by applying noise filters and then sampled in fixed-width sliding windows of 2.56 sec and 50% overlap (128 readings/window). The sensor acceleration signal, which has gravitational and body motion components, was separated using a Butterworth low-pass filter into body acceleration and gravity. The gravitational force is assumed to have only low frequency components, therefore a filter with 0.3 Hz cutoff frequency was used. From each window, a vector of features was obtained by calculating variables from the time and frequency domain.

Feature Information¶

  • Triaxial acceleration from the accelerometer (total acceleration) and the estimated body acceleration.
  • Triaxial Angular velocity from the gyroscope.
  • A 561-feature vector with time and frequency domain variables.
  • The activity label.
  • An identifier of the subject who carried out the experiment.

Citation¶

Davide Anguita, Alessandro Ghio, Luca Oneto, Xavier Parra and Jorge L. Reyes-Ortiz. A Public Domain Dataset for Human Activity Recognition Using Smartphones. 21st European Symposium on Artificial Neural Networks, Computational Intelligence and Machine Learning, ESANN 2013. Bruges, Belgium 24-26 April 2013.

Reducing the Dimensionality and Visualizing the Data:¶

  • We will perform a dimensionality reduction before visualizing the data points in 3D, reducing our dimensions from 561 features down to 3 components.
  • Can we discern visually, an intuitive sense of all 6 classes of the data, in a spatial way?
  • Is there a visible formal differentiation between these 6 groups of datapoints that is obvious?
  • We will capture the maximum variance explained within 3 principal components and plot them along 3 axes:

After reducing the original 561 features down to a set of 3 components that capture the majority of the original variance, we can see that there is a definite, discernable difference not only between the 2 major groups of activities (movement and non-movement), but also we can see the differentiation between the separate subgroups within these categories. Our first run with the random forest classifier has produced an accuracy score of 0.90906, with similar values for the recall and precision. We will seek to improve on the model's performance by adjusting the parameters.

Run 1: Use the criterion of the Gini index, using the measure of impurity:¶

  • Run a series of trees, from 3 to 70:
In [24]:
list_accuracy1 = []
list_confusion1 = {}

for i in range(3, 71):
    rf_classifier_gini = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=i, 
                                                criterion='gini', 
                                                max_depth=None, 
                                                min_samples_split=2, 
                                                min_samples_leaf=1, 
                                                min_weight_fraction_leaf=0.0, 
                                                max_features='auto', 
                                                max_leaf_nodes=None, 
                                                min_impurity_decrease=0.0, 
                                                min_impurity_split=None, 
                                                bootstrap=True, 
                                                oob_score=False, 
                                                n_jobs=1, 
                                                random_state=123, 
                                                verbose=0, 
                                                warm_start=False, 
                                                class_weight=None)
    rf_classifier_gini.fit(X_train, Y_train)
    y_hat = rf_classifier_gini.predict(X_test)
    list_accuracy1.append(accuracy_score(Y_test, y_hat))
    list_confusion1[i] = confusion_matrix(Y_test, y_hat)

Using the Gini index as our criterion for impurity, our accuracy score peaks at 34 decision trees with our random forest. There is a rapid rise in accuracy as the number of trees rises from 3 to 10, then the rate of increase reduces slightly. After about 40 trees, there is a point of diminishing returns with our model, as the performance gains are minimal while the computational expense increases.

Looking at the confusion matrix, we see that walking downstairs and especially walking upstairs are being misclassified as walking, and the walking downstairs is also being misclassified as walking upstairs.

Run 5: adjust the minimum impurity decrease to split nodes:¶

The weighted impurity decrease is defined as the following:

samples current node / total samples * (impurity - samples right child / total samples * right_impurity
                                                  - samples left child / total samples * left_impurity)

We will incrementally increase this threshold from the default of 0.0 to 0.1. Each node will be split if this split induces a decrease of the impurity greater than or equal to this value:

In [43]:
list_accuracy5 = []
list_confusion5 = {}
min_impurity_dec = [0.0, 0.005, 0.01, 0.015, 0.02, 0.025, 0.03, 0.035, 0.04, 0.045, 0.05, 0.055, 0.06, 0.065, 0.07, 0.075, 0.08, 0.085, 0.09, 0.095]

for i in min_impurity_dec:
    rf_classifier_impu = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=59, 
                                                criterion='entropy', 
                                                max_depth=20, 
                                                min_samples_split=2, 
                                                min_samples_leaf=1, 
                                                min_weight_fraction_leaf=0.0, 
                                                max_features='log2', 
                                                max_leaf_nodes=None, 
                                                min_impurity_decrease=i, 
                                                min_impurity_split=None, 
                                                bootstrap=True,

Increasing the impurity threshold for each node at the split is obviously not the correct direction to persue, as the accuracy scores trend downward rapidly as the threshold increases even slightly from 0. A two-hundredths of a point increase has had a tremendously detrimental effect on the model.

Results and Findings¶

With a relatively large number of decision trees in our random forest (59) we have been able to achieve 0.93621 accuracy. This may have been a byproduct of our dataset, with its 561 features, and would require a relatively large number of randomly sampled subsets of these features to create a more accurate consensus output classification. Measuring the information gain as we traverse down the trees with entropy, has also yielded better performance with this dataset.

There is a definite discernable difficulty in classifying the difference between walking downstairs, walking upstairs, and walking regularly. The observed activities of walking downstairs and especially walking upstairs are being misclassified as walking, and the walking downstairs is also being misclassified as walking upstairs. Even so, the rest of the human activities are able to be relatively easily classified with a high measure of accuracy.

Looking at the classification report below, we see that the recall is 0.94, as well as the precision and f1-score at 0.94.

Our model has the following hyperparameter settings:

  • number of trees: 59
  • criterion: Entropy
  • maximum depth of 20
  • minimum samples per split: 2
  • minimum samples per leaf: 1
  • max no. of features considered when looking for best split: log2(n_features)
  • no maximum limit on leaf nodes
  • minimum impurity decrease: 0.0
  • bootstrap: True (bootstrap aggregation is part of our random forest algo)
  • oob score: False (no out of bag samples used when estimating accuracy)
  • random state: 123 (allows us to replicate the random initial state)

The labels are encoded as:

  • 0 laying
  • 1 sitting
  • 2 standing
  • 3 walking
  • 4 walking downstairs
  • 5 walking upstairs
